('item-0139',139,'Norse Mythology','A · Hook','Norse Mythology — gate passage','gate','article','','400-460L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. PAIRED COLD GATE on one topic (''how the gods got their treasures / how stories survived''), both passages NEW (not read in any lesson). PASSAGE A — ''Thor''s Stolen Hammer'' (literary myth, ~280 words, target 450L): the giant Thrym steals Thor''s hammer Mjolnir and demands the goddess Freya as the price to return it; the gods solve the problem by disguising Thor as a bride to trick Thrym and win the hammer back. New characters and plot (Thrym, the disguise trick), reusing the unit''s taught LITERARY structures (problem-solution, character-action -> sequence, recount/central-message) so RL.3.1/RL.3.2/RL.3.3 are measured cold; illustrated with one image of the disguised ''bride'' lifting her veil at the giant''s feast — the picture must be read to know WHO is really under the veil, info the words hold back, giving a genuine RL.3.7 item. PASSAGE B — ''How Stories Survived Without Books'' (short INFORMATIONAL explainer on the SAME topic of how Norse tales/treasures were remembered and retold, ~120 words, target 445L, nonfiction): true facts linked by explicit logical connections — cause/effect (''Because no one could write the myths down, storytellers had to remember every line, so they repeated the tales at every feast'') and sequence (''First a poet learned the myth, next the poet taught it at gatherings, then children memorised it, and finally they retold it to the next village''). RI.3.8 is measured cold ONLY on Passage B, where naming the logical connection between particular sentences is authentic to the informational strand. Because both passages share the topic of Norse storytelling/treasures, the gate also supports a cross-text connection item (how the myth in A shows the very retelling-and-trickery the explainer in B describes), keeping the RI.3.8 measurement honest and giving a real two-text read. PER-ITEM NEAR-NEIGHBOUR DISTRACTOR DESIGN (every blueprint entry below is built with controlled foils, matching the lesson-CFU rigor): the two RL.3.1 mcq items use true-detail-from-Passage-A-but-not-the-asked-detail foils (plausible plot facts that don''t answer the stem); the RL.3.1 hot-text uses adjacent-line foils (lines next to the correct evidence line that restate but don''t prove); the RL.3.2 mcq uses too-narrow-detail vs too-broad-topic foils around the central message/lesson; the RL.3.2 drag-to-order uses plausible-but-out-of-order event sequencing foils (correct events, wrong order); the RL.3.3 msq uses other-character-action foils (deeds done by Thrym or the gods, not the asked character); the RL.3.3 match uses character-to-action swap foils (right actions paired to wrong character); the RL.3.7 mcq uses text-restated-not-image-added foils (options that repeat the words instead of what the veil/bride picture uniquely shows); the two L.3.4 mcq items use context-clue near-synonym foils (true-but-not-in-context word meanings), with one item adding a prefix/suffix or root clue for shades-of-meaning; the RI.3.8 mcq (on Passage B) uses connection-type confusion foils (cause/effect vs sequence vs comparison for the named sentence pair); the RI.3.8 drag-to-order (on Passage B) uses sequence-signal foils (first/next/then/finally steps shuffled into a plausible wrong order, plus one cause/effect line that is NOT a sequence step). Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
