('item-0210',210,'Space','A · Hook','Space — gate passage','gate','article','','400-460L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. UNSEEN topic (NOT taught in L1-L4): ''Comets: Icy Visitors'' — a 445L informational passage (~230 words) explaining what a comet is (a ball of ice and dust that orbits the Sun), why a comet grows a glowing tail when it comes close to the Sun (cause/effect: the Sun''s heat melts the comet''s ice), the time-order of a comet''s visit (far away -> nears the Sun -> tail forms -> swings away), with a labeled diagram of a comet (nucleus, tail) and an arrow showing its orbit path. The passage uses comparison language to set a comet beside a planet (BOTH orbit the Sun; BUT a comet grows a tail while a planet does not) for the RI.3.8 comparison items. Vocabulary present so L.3.4 can be probed cleanly: context-clue word ''glowing'' described as ''giving off bright light'' (for L.3.4.A); affix word ''returning'' = re- + return + -ing (for L.3.4.B); and a genuine known-BASE + derivational-suffix word ''dusty'' = dust + -y (made of/covered with dust) AND ''helpful'' = help + -ful for the real L.3.4.C root-word item — NO transparent two-word compounds, NO Latin-derived ''lunar''/''solar''. Dominant structures present so the gate can probe all assigned standards: main-idea+details, cause/effect, sequence, comparison (comet vs. planet), a diagram for RI.3.7, sentence-to-sentence connections for RI.3.8, and Tier-2/affix/root vocabulary (icy, glowing, frozen, distant, returning, dusty, helpful) for L.3.4. ALL gate MCQ/MSQ distractors are near-neighbours drawn from the taught Sun/planet/orbit/day-night schema (e.g., confusing a comet''s tail-cause with Earth''s spin, or a comet''s Sun-orbit with a moon''s orbit-of-a-planet). NOTE: per construct rules, every comet-vs-planet similarity/difference item in this gate is tagged RI.3.8 (comparison as a logical sentence connection), and RI.3.3 gate items are reserved for the genuine cause/effect (tail-forming) and time-order sequence (stages of the visit). Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
('item-0211',211,'Space','A · Hook','Space — gate','gate','mcq','RI.3.2+1 (Determine the main idea of the passage) [DF:B schema-mismap — near-neighbour distractors restate one true comet detail (a comet is icy; a comet has a tail) as if it were the whole-passage big idea]','400-460L','Unit-gate scored item ×2 (scaffolds OFF, near-neighbour). Stimulus = the unseen gate passage. Tag CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RI.3.2+1 (Determine the main idea of the passage) [DF:B schema-mismap — near-neighbour distractors restate one true comet detail (a comet is icy; a comet has a tail) as if it were the whole-passage big idea], format mcq.'),
('item-0212',212,'Space','A · Hook','Space — gate','gate','hot-text','RI.3.1+1 (Click the line that explicitly answers a question about the comet) [DF:A strategy-trap — lure lines are nearby comet sentences that sound on-topic but do not explicitly answer the stem''s question]','400-460L','Unit-gate scored item ×2 (scaffolds OFF, near-neighbour). Stimulus = the unseen gate passage. Tag CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RI.3.1+1 (Click the line that explicitly answers a question about the comet) [DF:A strategy-trap — lure lines are nearby comet sentences that sound on-topic but do not explicitly answer the stem''s question], format hot-text.'),
