('item-0282',282,'Ancient Rome','B · Bridge','Ancient Rome — gate passage','gate','article','','480-540L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. TWO PAIRED TEXTS ON THE SAME TOPIC (Roman soldiers), so a real RI.3.9 cross-text compare can be authored. TEXT 1 — ''A Roman Soldier''s Gear'' (~290 words, Lexile 525L, informational, DESCRIPTION-with-SEQUENCE): describes how a Roman legionary dressed and what he carried — the metal armor that protected his chest, the large shield he held in front of him, the strong leather sandals on his feet, and the heavy pack of food, tools, and a tent he carried on long marches. Walks step by step through a soldier getting ready: first the tunic, then the armor, then the shield and weapons, then the pack. New words are explained by nearby context clues (e.g., ''He strapped on his armor, the hard metal cover that protected his chest from spears.''). Tier-2 vocab: armor, shield, march, gear, protect, equipment. TEXT 2 — ''Fighting as a Legion'' (~150 words, Lexile 520L, informational, DESCRIPTION/CAUSE-EFFECT): describes how soldiers did NOT fight alone but worked together in large groups called legions; explains the ''tortoise'' formation where soldiers raised their shields together to form a wall and roof, so that arrows could not reach them; explains that because they trained and moved as one, a legion was very hard to beat. Context clues define new words (e.g., ''They formed a testudo, or tortoise, a tight block where every shield locked together.''). Tier-2 vocab: formation, legion, together, train, wall, defeat. The two texts share the SAME topic (Roman soldiers) but tell DIFFERENT parts: Text 1 is about ONE soldier''s gear and how he gets ready; Text 2 is about MANY soldiers fighting together as a group — enabling a genuine same/different comparison for the RI.3.9 item. Every gate slot uses near-neighbour distractors per the distractor_family tag embedded in its format field. Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
