('item-0351',351,'Native Americans','B · Bridge','Native Americans — gate passage','gate','article','','480-540L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. The gate supplies TWO short paired informational passages on the SAME topic (modern Native gatherings) so a genuine two-text compare (RI.3.9) is possible. PASSAGE A — ''The Powwow: A Gathering That Continues Today'' (informational, ~300 words, ~520L): explains that at a modern powwow, many different Native nations come together to dance in regalia, drum and sing, share food, sell handmade crafts, and pass traditions to children; it stresses that the powwow keeps alive the unit threads — many nations, the land, food, and stories — and that powwows are open, public, and held all across North America today. PASSAGE B — ''A Letter Home from the Salmon Festival'' (informational first-person account / report, ~250 words, ~500L): a child describes attending a Northwest Coast salmon festival where ONE nation honors the yearly salmon run with a feast, a first-salmon ceremony, canoe races, and elders telling the salmon''s story. Students have NOT read about powwows or salmon festivals in any lesson; both passages are new. Because both texts are informational and on the same topic (modern Native gatherings that keep traditions alive), students can compare the MOST IMPORTANT POINTS and KEY DETAILS across the two texts: how each gathering keeps traditions alive, who attends (many nations at a powwow vs. one nation at the salmon festival), and what activities each describes. The RI.3.9 msq and match items operate ACROSS Passage A and Passage B; the within-single-text items (RI.3.1, RI.3.2, RI.3.3) operate on Passage A. Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
