('item-0424',424,'Light & Sound','B · Bridge','Light & Sound — gate passage','gate','article','','480-540L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. TWO PAIRED INFORMATIONAL PASSAGES on the same topic (sensing in the dark with bounced sound), each about 280-310 words, both 500-520L, presented side by side so students can compare across them. PASSAGE A — ''How Bats Use Echoes to See in the Dark'' (about 300 words, 510L): explains that bats make high squeaks, the sound bounces off objects (an echo), and bats listen to the returning echo to find insects and avoid walls in darkness. This topic (echolocation) was NOT read in any lesson but draws on the unit''s reflection/bouncing and sound-vibration ideas, requiring transfer. The passage uses the word ''returning'' (as in ''the returning echo''): the prefix ''re-'' means ''back/again,'' and the surrounding sentence (''the squeak goes out, then the sound comes back to the bat as a returning echo'') gives a context clue — this is the named TARGET WORD for the L.3.4 prefix/context item, so L.3.4 is verifiably exercisable parallel to how RI.3.7 is anchored to the diagram. Passage A INCLUDES A LABELED DIAGRAM: a bat on the left, a curved arrow labeled ''squeak goes out'' pointing toward a moth on the right, and a curved arrow labeled ''echo comes back'' pointing from the moth back to the bat, plus a label ''wall'' behind the moth — so RI.3.7 (integrate text and visual) is genuinely exercisable. PASSAGE B — ''How Dolphins Find Their Way with Clicks'' (about 290 words, 510L): a second informational passage on the same topic of using bounced sound to sense surroundings, explaining that dolphins make clicking sounds underwater, the clicks bounce off fish and rocks, and dolphins listen for the returning sound to navigate and hunt where the water is dark or murky. Passage B is text-only. The two passages let students compare how bats and dolphins BOTH use bounced sound but in DIFFERENT surroundings (air vs. water). The EBSR item is built to require BOTH passages: Part A asks for the shared method both animals use to sense in the dark (drawn from across both texts); Part B asks the student to select the evidence sentence — one from Passage A AND one from Passage B — that together support the Part A answer, so the cross-text synthesis is real and the second passage is load-bearing, not decorative. The RI.3.8 hot-text targets how one idea in Passage A logically follows from another across sentences (the bat hears the echo, SO it knows where the moth is), and the L.3.5 match item targets shades-of-meaning among ''squeak,'' ''click,'' and ''echo'' as kinds/parts of bounced-sound sensing. Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
