('item-0608',608,'Classic Literature','C · Transfer','Classic Literature — gate passage','gate','article','','560-600L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. PRIMARY PASSAGE (unseen; NOT read in any lesson) -- ''The Lion and the Mouse'': an Aesop fable about a tiny mouse who is spared by a mighty lion and later gnaws through a hunter''s net to free that same lion, teaching that even the small can help the great, and that one kind act earns another. ~365 words; 595L; fable (literary); narrative story-grammar with a cause/effect turn (the mercy is the cause; the later rescue is the effect). Tier-2 vocab: mercy, mighty, gnaw, freedom, grateful, snare. PAIRED SECOND PASSAGE (also unseen; supplied so the RL.3.9 compare is real) -- ''The Dove and the Ant'': a short Aesop fable (~150 words; 585L; fable) in which a dove drops a leaf to save a drowning ant, and the grateful ant later bites a hunter''s heel to save the dove from a trap, teaching the same lesson that a small creature can repay a kindness and that kindness returns to the giver. Tier-2 vocab: drifting, grateful, repay, snare, rescue. NOTE on RL.3.10: RL.3.10 is demonstrated by the gate AS A WHOLE -- students independently read these grade-band-complex (band C, 560-600L) literary passages and answer without lesson scaffolding; it is documented as gate-level whole-passage independence rather than a single discrete skill check, and the lone MCQ tagged RL.3.10 below is a holistic main-idea/independent-comprehension prompt that requires reading the full unseen passage. Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
