('item-0666',666,'Ecology & Environment','C · Transfer','Ecology & Environment — gate passage','gate','article','','560-600L','Unit-gate UNSEEN passage. TWO short paired passages on the same topic (coral reefs), printed side by side so students can compare them. PASSAGE A — ''The Busy City Under the Sea'' (informational, cause-and-effect, ~210 words, ~575L): explains how a coral reef is built up over many years by tiny animals called coral polyps, names the many sea creatures (fish, crabs, sea turtles, eels) that depend on the reef for food and shelter, and describes what happens when ocean water gets too warm — the coral turns white and weak, which is called coral bleaching, and the animals that depend on it lose their home. PASSAGE B — ''A Letter from a Reef Scientist'' (informational/persuasive, reasons-and-evidence, ~200 words, ~590L): a marine scientist makes the point that people should help protect coral reefs, and backs it with reasons and evidence (reefs shelter one quarter of all ocean animals; warmer water from pollution causes bleaching; small choices like using less plastic and saving energy can keep the water cooler) and ends by urging readers to act. Both passages are about coral reefs and both mention bleaching from warm water, but Passage A explains how the reef works while Passage B argues what people should do about it. This topic was NOT read in any of the three lessons, which used wolves/rivers, arctic animals, and a river dam. Must be a topic NOT read in the lessons.'),
